    "instructions": [
      {
        "step_number": 1,
        "phase": "prep",
        "text": "In a large mixing bowl, combine the all-purpose flour, ajwain seeds, and salt. Pour in the melted ghee and rub the mixture between your fingers until it resembles coarse, wet sand.",
        "structured": {
          "action": "MIX",
          "temperature": null,
          "duration": null,
          "doneness_cues": null
        },
        "tips": []
      },
      {
        "step_number": 2,
        "phase": "prep",
        "text": "Gradually add cold water a few tablespoons at a time, kneading continuously until a stiff dough forms. Do not over-knead. Cover with a damp cloth and rest for at least 40 minutes.",
        "structured": {
          "action": "KNEAD",
          "temperature": null,
          "duration": "PT45M",
          "doneness_cues": {
            "visual": null,
            "tactile": "Dough should feel stiff and tight, not soft or sticky."
          }
        },
        "tips": []
      },
      {
        "step_number": 3,
        "phase": "cook",
        "text": "Heat 15ml of vegetable oil in a skillet over medium heat. Add the crushed coriander seeds and cumin seeds, frying for 30 seconds until fragrant.",
        "structured": {
          "action": "SAUTÉ",
          "temperature": null,
          "duration": "PT1M",
          "doneness_cues": null
        },
        "tips": []
      },
      {
        "step_number": 4,
        "phase": "cook",
        "text": "Add the grated ginger and minced green chilies. Sauté for another minute, then stir in the green peas and cook until slightly softened.",
        "structured": {
          "action": "SAUTÉ",
          "temperature": null,
          "duration": "PT2M",
          "doneness_cues": null
        },
        "tips": []
      },
      {
        "step_number": 5,
        "phase": "cook",
        "text": "Stir in the coarsely mashed potatoes, amchur powder, garam masala, and salt. Mix thoroughly to coat the potatoes in spices, cooking for 3 minutes to dry out any excess moisture.",
        "structured": {
          "action": "MIX",
          "temperature": null,
          "duration": "PT3M",
          "doneness_cues": null
        },
        "tips": []
      },
      {
        "step_number": 6,
        "phase": "prep",
        "text": "Remove the filling from heat, stir in the fresh cilantro, and transfer to a wide plate. Allow the filling to cool to room temperature completely.",
        "structured": {
          "action": "COOL",
          "temperature": null,
          "duration": "PT30M",
          "doneness_cues": null
        },
        "tips": []
      },
      {
        "step_number": 7,
        "phase": "assemble",
        "text": "Divide the rested dough into 6 equal portions. Roll one portion into a smooth ball, flatten it slightly, and roll it with a rolling pin into an 8-inch oval shape. Cut the oval horizontally through the center to create two semi-circles.",
        "structured": {
          "action": "ROLL",
          "temperature": null,
          "duration": null,
          "doneness_cues": null
        },
        "tips": []
      },
      {
        "step_number": 8,
        "phase": "assemble",
        "text": "Take one semi-circle, lightly moisten the straight edge with water, and fold it into a cone shape, overlapping the edges slightly. Press the seam firmly to seal completely.",
        "structured": {
          "action": "SHAPE",
          "temperature": null,
          "duration": null,
          "doneness_cues": null
        },
        "tips": []
      },
      {
        "step_number": 9,
        "phase": "assemble",
        "text": "Fill the cone with 2 to 3 tablespoons of the cooled potato filling, leaving a small border at the top. Moisten the upper inner edges with water, pinch them together to close the cone, and make a small pleat on the seam side so the samosa sits flat.",
        "structured": {
          "action": "ASSEMBLE",
          "temperature": null,
          "duration": null,
          "doneness_cues": null
        },
        "tips": []
      },
      {
        "step_number": 10,
        "phase": "cook",
        "text": "Heat the remaining vegetable oil in a heavy-bottomed pot to exactly 160C or 320F. Fry the samosas in batches of 3 or 4 for 12 to 15 minutes, turning occasionally, until the crust is deep golden brown and completely crisp without blisters.",
        "structured": {
          "action": "FRY",
          "temperature": {
            "celsius": 160,
            "fahrenheit": 320
          },
          "duration": "PT15M",
          "doneness_cues": {
            "visual": "Deep golden brown crust with a matte, unblistered surface.",
            "tactile": null
          }
        },
        "tips": []
      },
      {
        "step_number": 11,
        "phase": "finish",
        "text": "Remove the samosas with a slotted spoon and drain on a wire rack. Let them cool slightly before serving.",
        "structured": {
          "action": "REST",
          "temperature": null,
          "duration": "PT5M",
          "doneness_cues": null
        },
        "tips": []
      },
      {
        "step_number": 12,
        "phase": "finish",
        "text": "To serve as chaat, place two warm samosas on a plate and lightly crush the centers to open them up. Drizzle generously with whisked plain yogurt, mint chutney, and tamarind chutney. Garnish heavily with sev and a vibrant sprinkle of chaat masala.",
        "structured": {
          "action": "PLATE",
          "temperature": null,
          "duration": null,
          "doneness_cues": null
        },
        "tips": []
      }
    ],
    "troubleshooting": [
      {
        "symptom": "Blisters forming on the outside of the samosa crust during frying",
        "likely_cause": "The frying oil is too hot when the samosas are first added",
        "prevention": "Ensure the oil is strictly maintained at 160C (320F). A lower initial frying temperature slowly crisps the crust without creating air pockets.",
        "fix": "Reduce heat immediately. Blistered samosas will still taste delicious, but the textural aesthetics cannot be reversed once formed."
      },
      {
        "symptom": "Samosas break open in the oil",
        "likely_cause": "Seams were not sealed tightly with water, or the pastry was rolled too thin",
        "prevention": "Always use water to seal the edges and press firmly. Ensure the pastry is roughly 2mm thick.",
        "fix": "Remove broken samosas from the oil immediately to prevent the filling from ruining the frying oil. Cannot be fixed once burst."
      },
      {
        "symptom": "Dough feels too soft and stretchy to hold a shape",
        "likely_cause": "Too much water was added during kneading, or it was over-kneaded",
        "prevention": "Add water very gradually. The dough should be noticeably stiff and require effort to bring together.",
        "fix": "Knead in a small dusting of extra flour and let the dough rest longer to relax the gluten before attempting to roll."
      }
    ],
    "chef_notes": [
      "The fat-to-flour ratio, known as moyen in Indian cookery, is the primary secret to a flaky, crumbly shortcrust. Take the time to rub the ghee into the flour until it looks uniformly like wet sand before adding any water.",
      "A cold filling is strictly mandatory. If you fill the dough cones with warm potato mixture, steam will release inside the raw pastry, causing immediate sogginess and breakage during frying.",
      "For a baked alternative, brush the shaped, un-fried samosas generously with vegetable oil and bake on a parchment-lined tray at 200C (400F) for 25-30 minutes, flipping halfway through until golden.",
      "Chaat masala is an incredibly distinctive spice blend featuring black salt (kala namak) and dried mango powder. Its funky, sulfuric, and tart profile is essential for achieving an authentic street food flavor."
    ],
    "cultural_context": "Samosas originally traveled to the Indian subcontinent from the Middle East and Central Asia along ancient trade routes. Over centuries, they evolved into a deeply beloved Indian staple, particularly in Punjab, where the flaky pastry is matched with a hearty, spiced potato filling. Serving them as a loaded chaat represents the Indian street food philosophy of balancing textures and extreme flavors: sweet, sour, spicy, crunchy, and cooling all in one bite.",
